# NestJS Conventions

## File Naming

| Type | Pattern |
|------|---------|
| Module | `*.module.ts` |
| Controller | `*.controller.ts` |
| Service | `*.service.ts` |
| Unit test | `*.spec.ts` |
| E2E test | `*.e2e-spec.ts` |

Each domain lives in its own folder: `src/bands/`, `src/albums/`, etc.

## Module Structure

```typescript
@Module({
  imports: [TypeOrmModule.forFeature([Band])],
  controllers: [BandsController],
  providers: [BandsService],
})
export class BandsModule {}
```

## Dependency Injection

Always use constructor injection with `private readonly`:

```typescript
constructor(private readonly bandsService: BandsService) {}
```

## Controllers

- Use `@Render('template-name')` for SSR Pug views — no manual `res.render()`.
- Return a plain object from the handler; NestJS passes it to the template as locals.
- Route params via `@Param()`, query via `@Query()`, body via `@Body()`.

## Services

- All DB interactions live in the service, never in the controller.
- Return domain objects or typed DTOs — no raw query results leaked to the controller.

## Cross-cutting Concerns

Shared logic (guards, pipes, interceptors, decorators) goes in `src/common/`.
